  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is indeed a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The process makes the money appear to come from legitimate sources.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is a federal crime under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, which is codified in **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** and **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**. These statutes make it illegal to knowingly conduct or attempt to conduct any financial transaction involving the proceeds of unlawful activity with the intent to promote the illegal activity, evade taxes, or conceal the source of the funds.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe and may include:\n- Substantial fines (often in the hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars),\n- Imprisonment (up to 20 years or more per count),\n- Forfeiture of assets involved in the laundering scheme.\n\nThe exact penalties depend on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and other factors. Money laundering is taken very seriously by law enforcement and regulatory agencies worldwide, including the **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)** and the **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)** in the United States.",
